[size=4][b]What[/b][/size]

[size=3]Reshape vendor prices to taste. Keep the vanilla per-stock scaling, flatten it out, scale it up or down, or any mix — buy side and sell side are independent. Vendor tier progression keeps tracking the real value of every trade, so the level-up bar still advances even when you're paying flat prices.[/size]

[list]
[*][size=3][b]Dynamic Buy Pricing[/b] (toggle, on by default) — vanilla raises a vendor's asking price as their stock of an item runs low. Turn this off and every purchase is at the flat base price no matter how empty the shelf gets.[/size]
[*][size=3][b]Buy Price Multiplier[/b] (slider, 0.1 to 5.0, default 1.0) — final multiplier on every buy price. 0.5 is half price, 2.0 is double. Stacks with the toggle above.[/size]
[*][size=3][b]Dynamic Sell Pricing[/b] (toggle, on by default) — vanilla drops a vendor's pay as their stock of an item piles up. Turn this off and every sale pays the flat sell price no matter how many they already have.[/size]
[*][size=3][b]Sell Price Multiplier[/b] (slider, 0.1 to 5.0, default 0.75) — final multiplier on every sell price. 0.75 is the vanilla rate (vendors pay three-quarters of base). Raise it for easier income, lower it for a tighter economy. Stacks with the toggle above.[/size]
[/list]

[size=3]No perks or techs needed — settings apply the moment you install the mod, and existing prices in your save normalise the next time you open a vendor. If you're upgrading from a previous version, your old "Remove Inflation" and "Remove Deflation" choices are carried across to the new settings on first launch.[/size]

